data.text:
Lewes, DE, USA

Latitude and longitude coordinates are: 38.781082, -75.157150.

Lewes is a small coastal incorporated city located on the Delaware Bay, in eastern Sussex County, eastern Delaware, United States. Also known as "First Town, First State", Lewes was founded by the Dutch settlers on June 3, 1631 and incorporated on February 2, 1818. There are many sites in the city that were listed on the National Register of Historic Places such as Cool Spring Presbyterian Church, St. George's Chapel, Cape Henlopen Archeological District, Fisher's Paradise, William Russell House, Coleman House, and so on. Ryves Holt House, located at 218 2nd Street, is the oldest building in the state. You can take a tour to visit this 17th-century house. Lewes is home to Sussex Consortium and Hugh R. Sharp Campus of The University of Delaware. Points of interest in the city are Lewes Beach, The Lewes Historical Society Main Campus, Lewes Lighthouse, Harbor of Refuge Lighthouse, 1812 Memorial Park, Stango Park, Great Marsh Preserve, Beach Plum Island Nature Preserve, Fort Miles Historical Area, and Cape Henlopen State Park.
